Merge pull request #1410 from NyanKiyoshi/feature/graph-models/combined-include-exclude

Graph-models now permit the combination of includes and excludes

Graph-models now permit the combination of includes and excludes

This change allows users to provide both --include (-I) and
--exclude (-X) to filter given wildcard patterns, while being still
able to only include given model names or given wildcards to match.

For example, one might want to exclude all models, using --include,
then filter out some unwanted models through --exclude, e.g. M2M serving
as translation service.

This would result to the following usage:
./manage.py -I 'Attribute*' -X '*Translation'

Which basically tells graph-models to exclude all models, and only
keep the ones having their name starting by "Attribute" and remove
any of those that ends by the word "Translation".

Fix for 1.11 still using MIDDLEWARE_CLASSES.

We're upgrading to Django 1.11, but not (yet) using
`settings.MIDDLEWARE`. However, at runtime it defaults to `None`, which
results in `TypeError: argument of type 'NoneType' is not iterable` when
running `runserver_plus`. This approach allow for both styles of
middleware in Django < 2.0.

someone editing the file for optparse-specific functionality (which
should not be happening).

Fix admin_generator incompatible "default" identifier raising TypeError.

In admin_generator.py we change to the argparse "default" string replace
style and update ProxyParser to handle the necessary replacement for
optparse. The 3.5.1 docs for argparse state: "The help strings can
include various format specifiers to avoid repetition of things like the
program name or the argument default. The available specifiers include
the program name, %(prog)s and most keyword arguments to add_argument(),
e.g. %(default)s, %(type)s, etc." The use of "most" is ambiguous and in
preliminary testing, this functionality is at least missing for the
kwarg "action". It is not the intent of CompatibilityBaseCommand or
ProxyParser to add functionality to optparse, so we make no effort to
handle whatever other kwargs may be supported as formatted
identifiers in argparse, as the optparse docs only mention %default
in the help string. %prog exists in optparse only in the usage and
version strings.

Resolve RemovedInDjango110Warning for OptParser and NoArgsCommand.

The BaseCommand OptParser and NoArgsCommand RemovedInDjango110Warnings
are really two sides of the same coin. We need to provide a
compatibility layer between OptParser and ArgParse, and NoArgsCommand
is a wrapper around BaseCommand that simply ensured no arguments were
added to the command. To update NoArgsCommand, by sub-classing
BaseCommand and changing handle_noargs() to handle(), in a Command that
does not add options, would simply expose the other deprecation.

To resolve these, we use a sub-class of BaseCommand to dynamically
generate an options list from the provided add_arguments() of a
sub-class. This way the API is the same when Django < 1.8 support is
removed and all that needs to change in the command files is an import.
Implementation wise, for BaseCommand, AppCommand, and LabelCommand the
compatibility classes are a drop-in while changing to the new format of
defining add_arguments() rather than appending to options. For
NoArgsCommand, we need to change handle_noargs() to handle() with the
appropriate function signature. When changing to parser.add_argument(),
we must also be sure that any 'type=' kwarg from make_option() is
converted to an actual type (e.g. str, int) rather than a string of the
type name.

Merge pull request #548 from jdufresne/master

sqldiff: Two fixes for MySQL backend

Use set() instead of dict() to hold unsigned columns.

When looking for unsigned columns, we only inspect the key of the
dictionary. This is the operation sets are optimized for.

Inspect AUTO_INCREMENT status from the database instead of assuming.

Previously, if the primary key was numeric, it was assumed the DB
representation was AUTO_INCREMENT. This may not actually be
true. Better to inspect the database and get the actual state of the
paramter.

File "-/django_extensions/management/commands/dumpscript.py", line 718, in get_attribute_value

sqldiff | Fixed bug with --output_text option and notnull-differ text

Using the --output_text option a bug was raised when a notnull-differ difference
was detected.
The previous output text message for a notnull-differ difference was
"field '%(1)s' null differ: db='%(3)s', model='%(2)s'".
However only 2 parameters were available in diff_args (l.488) ; the name of the model
and whether you should 'SET' or 'DROP' the NULL contraint in the database.

sqldiff | Show differences for not managed tables

When meta.managed == False was set in one model, sqldiff was considering
the model but not its fields. The output of sqldiff showed that all columns of
the table should be dropped in the database.
Now we show the differences from db to its associated django models.

support mysql options files in reset_db

Django supports mysql option files
(see https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/ref/databases/#connecting-to-the-database).

This commit adds support for pulling in connection data from a
mysql options file for `reset_db`. This code follows the priority
order as given in the documentation above:

    OPTIONS.
    NAME, USER, PASSWORD, HOST, PORT
    MySQL option files.

Add option to show_urls to set the language

Add option to show_urls to set the language

This is really useful if you use i18n_patterns, as if en-us is not in
settings.LANGUAGES you will get an error for show_urls along the lines of:

    Error occurred while trying to load urls: The active language en-us is
    not in the list of configured languages: [u'en', u'es']

So the option added is -l --language= which allows you to set the
language code.  It's useful to be able to check all sometimes, as with
some systems (eg django-cms) the URL itself is i18n'ed.

Merge pull request #374 from Kronuz/patch-2

Strip quotes from constraints

Merge pull request #373 from Kronuz/patch-1

Table inheritance support in sqldiff

Strip quotes from constraints

"order", "limit" and perhaps others are quoted so the error: `field 'order' parameters differ: db='integer CHECK (""order"" >= 0)', model='integer CHECK ("order" >= 0)'` was being received from comparing PostgreSQL constraints. To fix this, strip quotes.

Table inheritance support in sqldiff

This patch adds inheritance support to sqldiff by recursing only if the model is a proxy model. Otherwise return local fields that are not ManyToManyFields. Additionally, models that are not managed should not return any fields whatsoever.

Fix #329

Removing contribute_to_class doesn't break any existing test and solves
the issue with multi-table inheritance described at #329 and highlighted
by the assertions added in 25b1e260769e418d0e4033e864a726e249dddbe2

contribute_to_class had been added as a workaround for Django
bug https://code.djangoproject.com/ticket/13696 Unfortunately this was
not the right thing to do as it has unwanted side-effects. An auto
field is an implicit primary added automatically by Django.
UUIDField is not an auto field.  The inline editing bug has to be
fixed in Django. django_extensions' UUIDField was doing the right
thing when it wasn't pretending to be an auto field.

Added option to rename gzipped files when --gzip is True; the renaming is done by simply appending '.gz' to the original file name. This way if you run sync_media_s3 once and want to do so again but with --gzip, by also including the option --renamegzip, the newly uploaded assets will be 'originalname.gz' instead of 'originalname', thus avoiding unintentionally replacing the assets uploaded during the first run of sync_media_s3. More generally, use --renamegzip if you want an easy way of differentiating your uploaded gzipped assets from the same uploaded non-gzipped versions.

Adding in a new command export_emails (and self to AUTHORS)

Supports exporting user emails in the following formats:
    address* - simple '"full name" <addr@host.com>;' format, one per line.
    google   - CSV file suitable for google import.
    outlook  - CSV file suitable for outlook import.
    linkedin - CSV file suitable for linkedin groups pre-approve import.

*defaults to 'address'

User listing can be filtered by group name.

output is to stdout unless optional filename is supplied as an argument.

Usage: manage.py export_emails [options] [output file]

Export user email address list in one of a number of formats.

Options:
  --settings=SETTINGS   The Python path to a settings module, e.g.
                        "myproject.settings.main". If this isn't provided, the
                        DJANGO_SETTINGS_MODULE environment variable will be
                        used.
  --pythonpath=PYTHONPATH
                        A directory to add to the Python path, e.g.
                        "/home/djangoprojects/myproject".
  --traceback           Print traceback on exception
  -g GROUP, --group=GROUP
                        Limit to users which are part of the supplied group
                        name
  -f FORMAT, --format=FORMAT
                        output format. May be one of 'address', 'google',
                        'outlook', 'linkedin'.
  --version             show program's version number and exit
  -h, --help            show this help message and exit

The latter required some pretty big changes, but from my (still limited) understanding of the dot format this is a bit cleaner then before as it generated all model nodes first and relations after that.
